# JFTL reference test corpus — chunk 7.
# Covers source lines ~1827-1897: bsearch, and date functions (strftime/
# strflocaltime/mktime/gmtime/strptime). Continues the ID sequence (361+)
# from chunk 6.
#
# Date-function conversions required reverse-engineering three offset rules
# between jq's "broken-down time" array and Python's time.struct_time,
# since I can't execute either side to check directly:
#   month: jq_month  = python_tm_mon - 1        (jq is 0-indexed)
#   wday:  jq_wday    = (python_tm_wday + 1) % 7 (jq: Sun=0; Python: Mon=0)
#   yday:  jq_yday    = python_tm_yday - 1       (jq is 0-indexed)
# Derived these by working backward from the one concrete gmtime example in
# the source (timestamp 1425599507 -> 2015-03-05, a Thursday, yday 63) —
# reasonably confident in the arithmetic, but this is hand-derived, not
# verified against a real jq. Spot-check before trusting.
#
# Also: gmtime's seconds field can carry a fractional part (see the
# "gmtime[5]" test), but Python's time.gmtime() truncates tm_sec to an int
# — recombined the fractional remainder manually.
#
# Same caveats as chunks 1-6: not engine-verified, best-effort tier calls.
# No lambdas anywhere (see chunk 6's note on py_expr.py rejecting them);
# used $pyrun= with real local-variable assignment instead, where binding
# an intermediate value made the expression far more readable than repeating
# an expensive call many times over.

[361-dates]
LEVEL=eval
JQ = {{{
bsearch(0,1,2,3,4)
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[1,2,3]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
-1
0
1
2
-4
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyeval=[(p if p < len(_) and _[p]==n else -(p+1)) for n in (0,1,2,3,4) if (p := __import__('bisect').bisect_left(_,n)) or True]"}
}}}
TRANSFORM=stream
COMMENT=Walrus (:=) inside the comprehension's "if" clause binds bisect_left's result once per iteration without needing a lambda; "or True" makes that filter clause always pass. Streaming jq's 5 outputs collected into one array.

[362-dates]
JQ = {{{
bsearch({x:1})
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[{ "x": 0 },{ "x": 1 },{ "x": 2 }]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
1
}}}
SKIP=needs a dict-aware comparator for bsearch; Python's bisect can't order dicts, and building one without lambda/def isn't worth it for one test.

[363-dates]
JQ = {{{
try ["OK", bsearch(0)] catch ["KO",.]
}}}
INPUT = {{{
"aa"
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
["KO","string (\"aa\") cannot be searched from"]
}}}
SKIP=needs try/catch.

[364-dates]
LEVEL=eval
JQ = {{{
strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[2015,2,5,23,51,47,4,63]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
"2015-03-05T23:51:47Z"
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyeval=__import__('time').strftime('%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ', (_[0], _[1]+1, _[2], _[3], _[4], _[5], 0, 1, 0))"}
}}}
COMMENT=Month field needs +1 to convert jq's 0-indexed month back to Python's 1-indexed tm_mon. This format string doesn't use %a/%A/%j, so the dummy wday/yday/isdst padding (0,1,0) never actually gets read.

[365-dates]
LEVEL=eval
JQ = {{{
strftime("%A, %B %d, %Y")
}}}
INPUT = {{{
1435677542.822351
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
"Tuesday, June 30, 2015"
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyeval=__import__('time').strftime('%A, %B %d, %Y', __import__('time').gmtime(_))"}
}}}
COMMENT=Timestamp input, so gmtime() computes weekday/month correctly on its own — no manual field math needed here, unlike the array-input cases.

[366-dates]
LEVEL=eval
JQ = {{{
strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[2024,2,15]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
"2024-03-15T00:00:00Z"
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyeval=__import__('time').strftime('%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ', (_[0], _[1]+1, _[2], _[3] if len(_) > 3 else 0, _[4] if len(_) > 4 else 0, _[5] if len(_) > 5 else 0, 0, 1, 0))"}
}}}
COMMENT=Input array only has 3 fields; padded missing hour/min/sec with 0, matching jq's apparent default here.

[367-dates]
LEVEL=eval
JQ = {{{
mktime
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[2024,8,21]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
1726876800
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyeval=__import__('calendar').timegm((_[0], _[1]+1, _[2], _[3] if len(_) > 3 else 0, _[4] if len(_) > 4 else 0, _[5] if len(_) > 5 else 0, 0, 1, 0))"}
}}}
COMMENT=calendar.timegm treats its tuple as UTC (unlike time.mktime, which is local-time and would be wrong here) — same month-offset and padding as 366.

[368-dates]
LEVEL=run
JQ = {{{
gmtime
}}}
INPUT = {{{
1425599507
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
[2015,2,5,23,51,47,4,63]
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyrun=t = __import__('time').gmtime(_)\nsec = t.tm_sec + (_ - int(_))\nreturn [t.tm_year, t.tm_mon - 1, t.tm_mday, t.tm_hour, t.tm_min, sec, (t.tm_wday + 1) % 7, t.tm_yday - 1]"}
}}}
COMMENT=Bound gmtime(_) once via a real local variable (run tier) instead of calling it 8 times in one giant expression — applies all three offset rules from the chunk header, plus recombining the fractional-second remainder that tm_sec alone would drop.

[369-dates]
LEVEL=eval
JQ = {{{
gmtime[5]
}}}
INPUT = {{{
1425599507.25
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
47.25
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$pyeval=__import__('time').gmtime(_).tm_sec + (_ - int(_))"}
}}}
COMMENT=Only the seconds field is needed here, so a single (mildly redundant) expression is fine without dropping to run tier.

